          "body": "Verses 29-31 do not feel like the chapter's center, but they are. *The time has been shortened* (ho kairos sunestalmenos estin) — the appointed time has been *wrapped up*, *furled*, like sails before harbor. The five-fold *hōs mē* (as though not) follows: those who have wives as though they had none, those who weep as though they did not weep, those who rejoice as though they did not, those who buy as though they did not possess, those who use the world as not consumed by it. *For the form (schēma) of this world is passing away* — present tense, already in process. Paul is not commanding emotional flatness or marital indifference; he is commanding eschatological detachment. Every legitimate good of the present age — marriage, grief, joy, possessions, the use of created things — is to be held loosely, because the configuration that holds them is dissolving. This is the engine behind Paul's preference for singleness, his counsel to remain in calling-state, his calmness about slavery. The Christian's center of gravity is in the age to come."
